</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">
This species is the most variable and has the largest distribution in the genus (Central America and Caribbean throughout Amazon basin). Such variation is 
<pageBreakToken pageId="7" pageNumber="22" start="start">product</pageBreakToken>
of its phenotypic plasticity and wide ecological range, and is responsible for making this species hard to be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Martinella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="iquitoensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="22">Martinella iquitoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as discussed above). Nonetheless, this high variation may also be seen as an evidence of a species complex, in which case, additional studies would be needed. For a complete list of synonyms see 
<bibRefCitation author="Gentry, AH" journalOrPublisher="University of Gothenburg, Stockholm" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" pagination="1 - 173" refId="B3" refString="Gentry, AH, 1977. Flora of Ecuador. University of Gothenburg, Stockholm: 1 - 173" title="Flora of Ecuador" year="1977">Gentry (1977)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
